It appears there's little point in the 30+ billion parameter models these days. With fine tuning, 13B LLaMa-based models seem to largely match or beat the bigger ones. And I'm not hearing about 65B parameter LLaMa at all anymore.

With 4-bit GPTQ, a 13B model works just fine on a "normal" consumer GPU. The weird thing about GPTQ is that it actually seems to improve the performance of at least some models, which kind of blows my mind.

The number of fine-tuned models has exploded, the same way Stable Diffusion models have.

Also, there seems to be an LLM version of Rule 34: if it exists, there's an LLM that can write porn about it.

The way "censorship" works is that the fine-tuning datasets give examples of "illegal" questions (like how to build a pipe bomb, say), and a "canned" response, something like "I can't help you do anything illegal or that might hurt someone." The problem with this approach is that it doesn't actually work; it's easy to "prompt engineer" one's way around, because the information is still in the model. You just have to follow another "route" to get to it.

As an example, instead of directly asking how to build a pipe bomb, ask your chatbot to write a movie scene in which a terrorist builds a pipe bomb. Since the "censored" training example matches the original question, and not the general concept of building a pipe bomb.

There are ways to actually censor models and remove certain concepts entirely. The problem is that they damage the model. And I don't mean in some weird twisted "if it's not the average view of the Internet it's a lie" kind of way. Because we don't understand how the models actually represent information, removing a concept will harm the model's understanding of other, potentially unrelated, concepts.

The dismantling of the Australian COVID-19 case reporting is hiding the scale (or even existence) of the current wave of community transmission sweeping across the country.

From the health.gov.au data (faithfully extracted by @dbRaevn) here are 4 key metrics, on a log scale to compare waves:
- Cases (reported from PCR & RAT tests)
- Hospitalised cases
- Aged Care Staff cases
- PBS scripts (for oral treatments)

Its fairly clear that they each move up in down in close synchronisation as the waves and troughs have occurred. Each metric has stayed within fairly consistent ranges, apart from Cases which in a steady decline, making historical comparisons irrelevant.

I think the most consistent is Aged Care Staff cases, where there is still mostly mandating of testing and reporting. I do expect that to be eroding slowly to become less accurate, but it's probably the best we have.

See, I'm an old dog (56 today!) but the nature of my work (tech, mostly IT, mostly programmer/analyst stuff) means I have to be able to learn new tricks, and fast.

Shifting from being a reasonably long-term Mac user, and an inveterate (since 1986) UN*X user, to being a Windows user - really not a biggie.

After a whole career of trying to avoid Windows!

How, why? Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL). Plus my regular tools being multi-platform. My essentials are gVim, Visual Studio Code (VSC), pgAdmin, UpNote, Typora, FireFox, mSecure, Skype, Slack, Signal.

Having gVim work from my WSL Ubuntu install, through the Windows UI is pretty damn cool. So, the integration of WSL with the main UI is tight enough that it's not so different from using console on a Mac. The file system is obviously different, but there is a Linux shortcut in Windows Explorer (if they still call it that) so you don't have to worry about where the files actually are. So I can interact with git through the Ubuntu command prompt, whilst editing files using VSC. Just like on a Mac.

My first Macbook Air was super-special, PC ultrabooks were no where near it at the time. Now, however, well, I LOVE this Fujitsu Lifebook. And you're not paying the Apple Tax AND I am working with actual GNU/Linux through WSL, and my usual distribution, rather than some bastardised version of FreeBSD. Which means I can test DIRECTLY on the laptop, without having to copy files off to another machine, virtual or otherwise.

Do Macs still have ANY advantage, for me? Yes. Press and hold a key, then hit a digit to get diacritics. This is a significant advantage for me, because it means I can touch-type. Important for me, as I am writing in multiple languages, all the time. In terms of characters, the main languages are Danish, French, German, Swedish, Finnish (should be covered by German and Swedish) and possibly Spanish, so need the √±. But Windows HAS got better, in that it now has an on-screen keyboard, where long press allows you to choose alternate forms, very similar to how it works on iOS. But still not touch-typeable.

So far, no show-stoppers.
